# SQLAlchemy Rules

## Query Construction

- Prefer ORM/Core query builders (`select`, `update`, `delete`) and model/table helpers (`get_one`, `get_all`, `query_count`, `upsert`) over handcrafted SQL.
- Do not write manual SQL strings for standard reads/writes in tests or service logic.
- Use model columns and SQLAlchemy expressions directly instead of `text("SELECT ...")` patterns.

## DDL and Schema Operations

- Use SQLAlchemy DDL constructs when available (for example `CreateSchema`) instead of hand-built SQL strings.
- Keep schema/table operations structured through metadata and SQLAlchemy primitives.

## Raw SQL Escape Hatch

- Raw SQL is only acceptable for true edge cases that cannot be expressed cleanly with SQLAlchemy builders.
- When raw SQL is unavoidable, scope it narrowly and document why SQLAlchemy primitives were insufficient.
